AGI -&nbsp; "An obstacle to the administration of justice under Article 70 of the Rome Statute". This is the hypothesis of crime contained in a complaint received by the prosecutor's office of the International Criminal Court > in which the names of Prime Minister Giorgia&nbsp are indicated; Meloni and ministers Carlo&nbsp; Nordio&nbsp; and Matteo Piantedosi in relation to the Almasri case. To write to Aja, through his lawyers, he was a Sudanese refugee who already in 2019 told international investigators the tortures he and his wife suffered from General Almasri, when both had been imprisoned in Libya.
"The applicant, a Sudanese citizen of Darfur with refugee status in France, claims that his wife, himself and countless members of the group of which he is a member ('migrants') have been victims of numerous and continuous crimes," reads in the request sent to the prosecutor's office just after listening to the Chamber ministers&nbsp;Nordio&nbsp;e Piantedosi.
&nbsp;
Sources of our government report that at the moment there is no open proceedings against Italy by the International Criminal Court.' The Prosecutor of the CPI has not officially sent the complaint of the Sudanese citizen neither to the register nor to the judges but simply received an e-mail report, have specified the same sources.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Nordio, "everybody investigates everything"></h2>
"I believe that everyone in this world is investigating everything. We have faith in human justice, or rather, I postulate divine justice because the human one is often failable. Let's settle for what we have and see how it goes." He told Rai Radio1, guest of 'A Day from Pecora', the Minister of Justice Carlo&nbsp;Nordio, answering a question about the news of the press that spoke of a alleged file opened by the Cpi on the Italian Government. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Speaking of Almasri, the Guardasigilli said: "I think I'm sorry, but first of all we have to apply the laws, otherwise we go back to doing justice by ourselves. Humanly speaking, I would like every person who has committed a crime to be judged, if convicted and that the penalty is carried out according to the rules and procedures", adding that "the courts exist because they have to comply with the rules. Even yesterday we talked a lot about it saying 'yes', the warrant will be wrong but that is a torturer'. If we followed this criterion then neither the International Criminal Court or the Nuremberg Tribunal would make sense: the courts exist because they have to comply with the rules," he pointed out, "Nordio, underlining that "the idea that one is a torturer and that it must be punished as such, regardless of compliance with the rules, means deleting the very existence of international courts." &nbsp;
<h2> <br> Tajani, "would need to investigate the Cpi"> </h2>
"No comment on the International Criminal Court - said the Foreign Minister Antonio Tajani this morning about the indiscretions (unconfirmed) on the proceedings against Italy -. I have a lot of reservations about the Court's behaviour on this. Perhaps we must open an investigation into the Court, we must have clarifications on how it behaved. The act sent to Italy was null and void, I share 100% what the Minister&nbsp;Nordio said." &nbsp;
